{
  "Glaciers form when annual snowfall exceeds annual snowmelt over:": "",
  "A single winter season": "",
  "Many years, allowing snow to compress into firn and then glacial ice": "",
  "One complete year only": "",
  "A few weeks of heavy snowfall": "",
  "Glacier formation requires decades to centuries of accumulated snow that compacts under its own weight. Fresh snow first transforms into granular firn, and over time, continued compression forces out air pockets, converting the firn into dense glacial ice.": "",
  "What are the two main types of glaciers?": "",
  "Surface glaciers and underground glaciers": "",
  "Tropical glaciers and polar glaciers": "",
  "Alpine (valley) glaciers and continental ice sheets": "",
  "Freshwater glaciers and saltwater glaciers": "",
  "The two main types are alpine (valley) glaciers, which form in mountain valleys and flow downhill, and continental ice sheets, which are massive glaciers that cover large land areas. Today's ice sheets are found in Antarctica and Greenland.": "",
  "If all of Earth's glaciers and ice caps melted, global sea levels would rise approximately:": "",
  "200 meters": "",
  "65-70 meters": "",
  "10-15 meters": "",
  "1-2 meters": "",
  "Scientists estimate that the complete melting of all glaciers and ice sheets would raise global sea level by approximately 65 to 70 meters (about 215 feet). The Antarctic Ice Sheet alone contains enough ice to raise sea level by about 58 meters.": "",
  "A cirque is a glacial landform that is best described as:": "",
  "A deep crack in the surface of a glacier": "",
  "A bowl-shaped depression carved into a mountain by a glacier": "",
  "A long ridge of sediment deposited by a glacier": "",
  "A flat plain created by glacial meltwater": "",
  "A cirque is an amphitheater-shaped, bowl-like depression carved into the side of a mountain by the erosive action of a glacier. Cirques form at the head of a glacier where freeze-thaw weathering and glacial plucking gradually excavate the rock into a rounded hollow.": "",
  "Glacial valleys are typically shaped like the letter:": "",
  "W, with multiple ridges": "",
  "L, with one steep wall and one gentle slope": "",
  "V, with steep narrow walls": "",
  "U, with broad flat floors and steep sides": "",
  "Glaciers carve U-shaped valleys with broad, flat floors and steep, nearly vertical walls. This contrasts with V-shaped valleys carved by rivers. The massive weight and abrasive power of a glacier widens and deepens the valley, transforming its cross-section from V to U.": "",
  "Where is the majority of Earth's glacial ice found today?": "",
  "Greenland": "",
  "The Himalayan mountain range": "",
  "The Arctic Ocean sea ice": "",
  "Antarctica": "",
  "Antarctica holds approximately 90% of all glacial ice on Earth, with an ice sheet that covers about 14 million square kilometers. Greenland contains most of the remaining glacial ice, holding about 8% of the global total.": "",
  "A moraine is best described as:": "",
  "A lake formed inside a volcanic crater": "",
  "A ridge or mound of sediment and rock deposited by a glacier": "",
  "A river that flows beneath a glacier": "",
  "A deep crevasse in the center of a glacier": "",
  "A moraine is an accumulation of rock, soil, and debris that has been carried and deposited by a glacier. Terminal moraines form at the farthest point of glacial advance, while lateral moraines form along the glacier's sides.": "",
  "Glaciers move primarily through two processes:": "",
  "Internal plastic deformation and basal sliding": "",
  "Evaporation and condensation": "",
  "Wind push and tidal pull": "",
  "Thermal expansion and contraction": "",
  "Glaciers move through internal deformation, where ice crystals under pressure slowly flow like a very viscous fluid, and basal sliding, where meltwater at the base of the glacier lubricates the contact between ice and bedrock, allowing the glacier to slide forward.": "",
  "The snowline on a mountain refers to:": "",
  "The line where a glacier begins to melt": "",
  "The maximum depth of snow in a given year": "",
  "The elevation above which snow persists year-round": "",
  "The boundary between snow cover and bare ground on a satellite image": "",
  "The snowline (or equilibrium line) is the altitude above which snow accumulates faster than it melts and persists throughout the year. Above this line, conditions favor glacier formation. The snowline varies with latitude, being near sea level at the poles and at high elevations near the equator.": "",
  "Glacial erratics are:": "",
  "Large boulders transported and deposited far from their origin by glaciers": "",
  "Cracks that form on the surface of a glacier": "",
  "Fossilized organisms found in glacial ice": "",
  "Small streams of meltwater flowing under a glacier": "",
  "Glacial erratics are rocks or boulders that glaciers carry great distances from their source and deposit in areas with completely different geology. They are often recognizable because their rock type differs from the local bedrock, providing evidence of past glacial activity.": "",
  "What is firn?": "",
  "Frozen seawater found at the edges of ice shelves": "",
  "The thin layer of meltwater at the bottom of a glacier": "",
  "Water vapor released from melting glaciers": "",
  "Compacted granular snow that is an intermediate stage between fresh snow and glacial ice": "",
  "Firn is partially compacted granular snow that has survived at least one summer melt season. It represents the transitional stage between freshly fallen snow and glacial ice, with a density between that of snow and ice as air is gradually squeezed out over time.": "",
  "What is a crevasse?": "",
  "A type of moraine found at the end of a glacier": "",
  "A frozen waterfall on the side of a mountain": "",
  "A tunnel carved through rock by glacial meltwater": "",
  "A deep, open crack or fissure in the surface of a glacier": "",
  "A crevasse is a deep crack that forms in the brittle upper layer of a glacier due to stresses caused by the glacier's movement. Crevasses can be tens of meters deep and are a significant hazard for glacier travel, sometimes hidden by thin snow bridges.": "",
  "What is calving in glaciology?": "",
  "The process by which chunks of ice break off the edge of a glacier or ice shelf to form icebergs": "",
  "The compression of snow into ice over centuries": "",
  "The formation of crevasses on a glacier surface": "",
  "The growth of a glacier during a cold period": "",
  "Calving occurs when large pieces of ice fracture and break away from the front (terminus) of a glacier, ice shelf, or iceberg. When glaciers calve into the ocean, they produce icebergs. Calving is a major mechanism of mass loss for marine-terminating glaciers.": "",
  "What is glacial till?": "",
  "Frozen soil found in arctic regions": "",
  "Clear meltwater that flows from the base of a glacier": "",
  "Unsorted sediment of various sizes deposited directly by glacial ice": "",
  "The smooth, polished surface of bedrock beneath a glacier": "",
  "Glacial till is unsorted, unstratified sediment deposited directly by melting glacial ice. It contains a chaotic mixture of particle sizes ranging from fine clay to large boulders. Till is distinct from glacial outwash, which is sorted by meltwater streams.": "",
  "What is an ice shelf?": "",
  "A thick platform of ice that forms where a glacier or ice sheet flows into the ocean and floats on the water": "",
  "A ledge of ice that forms on the side of a mountain cliff": "",
  "A thin layer of sea ice that forms on the ocean surface each winter": "",
  "An iceberg that has become grounded on the seafloor": "",
  "An ice shelf is a thick floating platform of ice that forms where a glacier or ice sheet flows off the land and onto the ocean surface. Ice shelves are attached to the coastline and act as buttresses that slow the flow of glaciers behind them. Major ice shelves exist around Antarctica.": "",
  "What is the albedo effect as it relates to glaciers?": "",
  "The reflectivity of ice and snow surfaces, which bounce solar radiation back into space": "",
  "The insulating property of glacier ice that keeps the ground warm": "",
  "The tendency of glaciers to absorb all incoming sunlight": "",
  "The blue color of glacial ice caused by compressed air bubbles": "",
  "Albedo measures the fraction of incoming solar radiation that a surface reflects. Ice and snow have very high albedo (reflecting 80-90% of sunlight), which helps keep polar regions cool. As glaciers melt and expose darker land or ocean, albedo decreases, creating a positive feedback loop that accelerates warming.": "",
  "What is a glacial retreat?": "",
  "When a glacier splits into two separate ice masses": "",
  "When a glacier moves backward uphill against gravity": "",
  "When snowfall causes a glacier to become thicker without advancing": "",
  "When the terminus of a glacier recedes because melting exceeds accumulation": "",
  "Glacial retreat occurs when the rate of melting and calving at a glacier's terminus exceeds the rate of ice accumulation from snowfall. The glacier still flows forward, but its front edge (terminus) recedes because ice is lost faster than it is replenished.": "",
  "What is a drumlin?": "",
  "A narrow ridge connecting two mountain peaks": "",
  "A coastal sand dune shaped by ocean winds": "",
  "A streamlined, elongated hill of glacial till shaped by the movement of ice": "",
  "A deep lake formed inside a volcanic crater": "",
  "A drumlin is an elongated, teardrop-shaped hill made of glacial till or bedrock that was shaped by the flow of glacial ice over it. Drumlins are typically found in groups called drumlin fields, and their long axis indicates the direction of past ice flow.": "",
  "What is the zone of accumulation on a glacier?": "",
  "The lower area where glacial meltwater collects in pools": "",
  "The upper area of a glacier where snowfall exceeds melting, adding mass to the glacier": "",
  "The edge of a glacier where icebergs break off": "",
  "The middle section where the glacier is thickest": "",
  "The zone of accumulation is the upper portion of a glacier where annual snowfall exceeds annual melting. In this zone, new snow and ice are continuously added to the glacier's mass. The boundary between the accumulation and ablation zones is called the equilibrium line.": "",
  "What is permafrost?": "",
  "Ice that forms on the surface of rivers during winter": "",
  "A glacier that has not moved for over 100 years": "",
  "Ground that remains frozen for at least two consecutive years": "",
  "Snow that falls and immediately freezes on contact with the ground": "",
  "Permafrost is soil, rock, or sediment that remains at or below 0 degrees Celsius for at least two consecutive years. It is found in polar regions and high mountains and can extend hundreds of meters deep. Thawing permafrost due to climate change releases stored carbon and methane.": "",
  "A climate scientist examines ice core data from Greenland and discovers that air bubbles trapped in ice from 10,000 years ago contain significantly lower carbon dioxide levels than today's atmosphere. What does this evidence reveal?": "",
  "Ice cores trap ancient atmospheric gases, providing a record of past atmospheric composition and showing that CO2 levels have increased significantly": "",
  "Plants were more abundant 10,000 years ago and consumed all the carbon dioxide": "",
  "The ice core equipment malfunctioned and gave incorrect readings": "",
  "Carbon dioxide did not exist in the atmosphere 10,000 years ago": "",
  "Ice cores preserve tiny air bubbles that contain samples of the atmosphere from the time the ice formed. By analyzing these bubbles, scientists can reconstruct a detailed history of atmospheric composition going back hundreds of thousands of years, clearly showing the dramatic rise in CO2 since the Industrial Revolution.": "",
  "A coastal city at low elevation learns that a large Antarctic ice shelf is beginning to collapse. City planners are concerned even though the melting ice shelf itself will not raise sea levels significantly. Why are they still worried?": "",
  "The ice shelf collapse will cause massive tsunamis": "",
  "Without the buttressing ice shelf, the glaciers behind it will flow faster into the ocean, contributing to sea level rise": "",
  "The cold water from the melting ice shelf will freeze the city's harbor": "",
  "Ice shelf collapse always triggers volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Ice shelves act as buttresses that hold back the land-based glaciers behind them. When an ice shelf collapses, those glaciers accelerate their flow into the ocean, and it is this land-based ice entering the ocean that raises sea levels. The collapse of the Larsen B ice shelf in 2002 caused its tributary glaciers to speed up dramatically.": "",
  "A hiker in the Alps notices that a glacier's terminus is now 500 meters higher up the valley than it was in photographs from 50 years ago. The exposed rock below is polished and covered with scratches (striations). What can be concluded from these observations?": "",
  "The glacier has retreated due to increased melting, and the striations were carved by rocks embedded in the moving ice": "",
  "Earthquakes created the striations on the exposed rock": "",
  "The glacier has advanced significantly in the last 50 years": "",
  "River water flowing under the glacier caused the scratches": "",
  "The glacier has retreated 500 meters up the valley, meaning it is losing more ice through melting than it gains from snowfall. The striations (scratches) on the exposed bedrock were carved by rocks frozen into the base of the glacier as it moved forward, acting like sandpaper on the underlying rock.": "",
  "Scientists observe that Arctic sea ice cover in September has decreased by approximately 40% since 1979. A student asks why losing sea ice would accelerate further warming. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Sea ice produces a cooling gas that is released into the atmosphere": "",
  "Sea ice blocks warm ocean currents, so removing it allows warm water to flow north": "",
  "Without sea ice, cold air masses cannot form over the Arctic": "",
  "Replacing bright, reflective ice with dark ocean water decreases albedo, causing more solar energy to be absorbed": "",
  "This is the ice-albedo feedback loop. Sea ice reflects about 80% of incoming solar radiation, while dark ocean water absorbs about 94%. As ice melts and exposes more dark water, more solar energy is absorbed, further warming the ocean and melting even more ice in a self-reinforcing cycle.": "",
  "A geologist mapping a landscape in the midwestern United States finds a cluster of smooth, elongated hills all oriented in the same direction. She identifies them as drumlins. What can she infer from their orientation?": "",
  "The direction that a glacier flowed across this landscape in the past": "",
  "The orientation of fault lines beneath the surface": "",
  "The prevailing wind direction in the region": "",
  "The direction of ancient river channels": "",
  "Drumlins are streamlined hills shaped by glacial ice, with their long axis aligned parallel to the direction of ice flow. The steeper, blunt end faces the direction the ice came from, while the tapered end points in the direction the ice flowed. Groups of drumlins serve as reliable indicators of past glacial movement.": "",
  "Researchers studying permafrost in Siberia discover that thawing ground is releasing large amounts of methane gas. A student asks why this is especially concerning for climate change. What is the best response?": "",
  "Methane is a potent greenhouse gas, and its release creates a positive feedback loop that accelerates warming and further thawing": "",
  "Methane depletes the ozone layer, causing more UV radiation to reach Earth": "",
  "Methane cools the atmosphere, which paradoxically increases ice melting": "",
  "Methane reacts with oxygen to produce toxic smog in the atmosphere": "",
  "Methane is approximately 80 times more effective at trapping heat than carbon dioxide over a 20-year period. As warming thaws permafrost, trapped organic matter decomposes and releases methane, which causes more warming, which thaws more permafrost. This positive feedback loop could significantly amplify global warming beyond human-caused emissions alone.": "",
  "A community in the Himalayas depends on seasonal glacial meltwater for their drinking water and crop irrigation during the dry summer months. Scientists predict that the local glacier will disappear within 50 years. What is the most significant long-term impact for this community?": "",
  "They will experience severe flooding every year": "",
  "They will lose their reliable dry-season water supply as the glacier that stores water as ice disappears": "",
  "The community will be buried under glacial debris": "",
  "Average temperatures in the community will increase dramatically": "",
  "Glaciers act as natural water storage systems, accumulating snow in winter and releasing meltwater during warm, dry months when water demand is highest. Once the glacier disappears, this natural reservoir is gone, and the community must rely solely on seasonal rainfall, which may not meet their needs during the dry season.": "",
  "During a geology field trip, students observe a valley with a broad, flat bottom and steep walls in a mountainous region. Their professor asks them to determine whether the valley was carved by a river or a glacier. Which evidence would best indicate glacial origin?": "",
  "Sand dunes and wind-blown sediment on the valley floor": "",
  "V-shaped cross-section with a meandering stream on the floor": "",
  "Rounded pebbles at the bottom of the valley": "",
  "U-shaped cross-section, polished and striated bedrock, and unsorted till deposits": "",
  "Glacial valleys exhibit a distinctive combination of features: a U-shaped cross-section (unlike the V-shape of river valleys), polished and striated (scratched) bedrock from the abrasive action of debris-laden ice, and deposits of unsorted till containing mixed particle sizes from clay to boulders.": "",
  "An island nation with an average elevation of only 2 meters above sea level is concerned about climate projections showing continued glacial melting. Government officials ask scientists which ice sheet poses the greatest threat to them. What should the scientists say?": "",
  "The Antarctic Ice Sheet, because it contains enough ice to raise sea level by about 58 meters": "",
  "Arctic sea ice, because it covers the largest area": "",
  "The Alpine glaciers, because they are melting the fastest": "",
  "Himalayan glaciers, because they contain the most freshwater": "",
  "The Antarctic Ice Sheet holds approximately 26.5 million cubic kilometers of ice, enough to raise global sea level by about 58 meters if it all melted. Even partial melting poses an existential threat to low-lying island nations. The Greenland Ice Sheet, which could add about 7 meters, is the second greatest concern.": "",
  "A farmer living near a retreating mountain glacier notices that a new lake has formed behind a wall of loose debris at the glacier's terminus. Local officials warn that this could be dangerous. What is the specific hazard they are concerned about?": "",
  "The moraine dam could fail, causing a catastrophic glacial lake outburst flood": "",
  "The lake will attract wildlife that will damage crops": "",
  "The lake water is too acidic for any use": "",
  "The lake will freeze solid and expand the glacier back downhill": "",
  "Glacial lake outburst floods (GLOFs) occur when the moraine dam holding back a glacial lake fails suddenly, releasing a massive wall of water and debris downstream. These floods can be devastating to communities below. As glaciers retreat and create more moraine-dammed lakes, GLOF risk increases worldwide.": ""
}